{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":5306,"record_hash":"sha256:7625aed217bfeb02373ad67b89ab77d77ca5c4e6e74c2bf22ecb796181011b8a","timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:33:07.975Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:118-124) [added]\n[P2] Sensitive field names do not force redaction\n\n`field_name` is currently used only for exemptions, so values under keys like `password`, `token`, `api_key`, `authorization`, or `secret` can still be stored unchanged when they are short, low-entropy, dictionary-like, or UUID-shaped. A tiny local denylist before the entropy/UUID/path exemptions would close this without turning the POC into a full scanner.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:320-325) [added]\n[P2] Generic Git labels can preserve random hex\n\n`protected_git_hash_range()` treats field names like `object`, `parent`, `tree`, and `blob` as Git-labelled context. In arbitrary JSON payloads those names are not necessarily Git-specific, so a 40/64-char random-looking hex secret under one of those fields can be preserved instead of redacted. Narrowing field-name preservation to more explicit `*_sha`, `*_oid`, or `object_id`-style labels would make the exception tighter.\n\n## Finding 3 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:173-176) [added]\n[P2] Embedded UUIDs are preserved inside risky tokens\n\n`protected_spans()` preserves any UUID range even when the surrounding candidate is being redacted. The existing `sk-<uuid>-<random>` case stores the UUID portion, which can leak tenant/session/account identifiers for token formats that embed UUIDs. A stricter POC rule would preserve UUIDs only when the whole candidate is a UUID or when it has an approved ID label.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nOkay in this case lets once again did a performance test. i wanna make sure we are not doing something insane like quadratic scaling or worse. And if we can make some obvious tweaks around allocation reduction, less copying etc lets do it. But lets not go crazy and sacrifice readability\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T16:33:07.975Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:118-124) [added]\n[P2] Sensitive field names do not force redaction\n\n`field_name` is currently used only for exemptions, so values under keys like `password`, `token`, `api_key`, `authorization`, or `secret` can still be stored unchanged when they are short, low-entropy, dictionary-like, or UUID-shaped. A tiny local denylist before the entropy/UUID/path exemptions would close this without turning the POC into a full scanner.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:320-325) [added]\n[P2] Generic Git labels can preserve random hex\n\n`protected_git_hash_range()` treats field names like `object`, `parent`, `tree`, and `blob` as Git-labelled context. In arbitrary JSON payloads those names are not necessarily Git-specific, so a 40/64-char random-looking hex secret under one of those fields can be preserved instead of redacted. Narrowing field-name preservation to more explicit `*_sha`, `*_oid`, or `object_id`-style labels would make the exception tighter.\n\n## Finding 3 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:173-176) [added]\n[P2] Embedded UUIDs are preserved inside risky tokens\n\n`protected_spans()` preserves any UUID range even when the surrounding candidate is being redacted. The existing `sk-<uuid>-<random>` case stores the UUID portion, which can leak tenant/session/account identifiers for token formats that embed UUIDs. A stricter POC rule would preserve UUIDs only when the whole candidate is a UUID or when it has an approved ID label.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nOkay in this case lets once again did a performance test. i wanna make sure we are not doing something insane like quadratic scaling or worse. And if we can make some obvious tweaks around allocation reduction, less copying etc lets do it. But lets not go crazy and sacrifice readability\n"}]}}}